did you make your own rig or use a rigging plugin? either way, its likely a weight paint issue. make sure her eyeballs+freckles are fully weight painted to the head bone, stripes to arms etc. when using glb, theres something about the keyframing of extra joints beyond a 4+ dependency chain being "guesstimated" upon exporting which might alter the bone/animation output a bit.
terminal says this when i export:
>WARNING: There are more than 4 joint vertex influences.The 4 with highest weight will be used (and normalized).
make sure your weights are generous enough to help the final glb look correct. also dont forget to group animation as seperate NLA tracks and turn OFF "Optimize Animation Size" under the Animation dropdown in the glb export window.

Sweetheart Deal: Chapter Twenty-Two - The Warren

Welcome to Nuevo Carcangel, circa 2174. A century has passed since a plague killed half of humanity. No one living now knows why some of the survivors are called chimeras, nor how the plague created them - if it did.
Christina Marlowe, a private investigator and a fox-type chimera, has other concerns. She's living in one of the biggest city-states. What technology used to exist is gone. She knows the trains and streetcars, her trusty revolver, and that she needs a big case.
Nathaniel Berrymount may be it. He's nervous at first and rightly so. The signs point to a sweetheart deal that's meant to collapse, leaving the victor with everything.
Marlowe will have to think and talk fast as events pile up. A Boss wants his blueprints back. What do the buns of The Warren want? And can she keep her client from falling for her?

In this chapter, at last is the name of the game. Having survived yet another time when her tail might have been sent to the body farms - dead, that is - Marlowe heads to The Warren. High on her list of things to do is find the mysterious bun, Mother Uriah. Why would she have sent the word ruiadh - red - with her earlier message? It is the name of one of Marlowe's many aliases, but how would Mother Uriah know any of those? It has to be a coincidence.
But someone has to answer for this complicated mess of a case and why the cats had several tubes of blueprints. The answers are out there and The Warren is one of the few places Marlowe hasn't snuck into.
The first problem is getting in, and the buns don't exactly have a welcome mat out for predator chimeras. Marlowe might have finally met her match for wily and tricky.
